  <div class="hero-label">What's at stake — Energy</div>
  <h1 class="hero-title">One Cable.<br>One Province.</h1>
  <p class="hero-subtitle">PEI generates a fraction of its own electricity. The rest arrives via a single undersea cable from New Brunswick — a geographic dependency unlike any other Canadian province.</p>
  <hr class="hero-rule">

  <div class="fact-strip">
    <div class="fact-card">
      <div class="fact-num">300 MW</div>
      <div class="fact-label">maximum capacity of the NB Power submarine cable interconnect</div>
    </div>
    <div class="fact-card">
      <div class="fact-num">403 MW</div>
      <div class="fact-label">all-time PEI peak demand — January 25, 2026 at 5:44 PM</div>
    </div>
    <div class="fact-card">
      <div class="fact-num">~30%</div>
      <div class="fact-label">of electricity generated on-island (wind + backup turbines)</div>
    </div>
    <div class="fact-card">
      <div class="fact-num">86,000</div>
      <div class="fact-label">Maritime Electric customers — every home and business on PEI</div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="section">
    <h2 class="section-title">The grid dependency</h2>
    <div class="section-body">
      <p>Maritime Electric, PEI's primary utility, serves roughly 86,000 customers across the island. (Summerside operates its own municipal electric utility serving approximately 9,000 customers.) At any given moment, the vast majority of electricity consumed on PEI is generated in New Brunswick and transmitted via submarine cable across the Northumberland Strait.</p>

      <div class="cable-diagram">
        <div class="flow">
          <span class="node">NB Power grid</span>
          <span class="arrow">→</span>
          <span class="node">Submarine cable<br><small>~300 MW cap</small></span>
          <span class="arrow">→</span>
          <span class="node">Maritime Electric<br><small>PEI distribution</small></span>
          <span class="arrow">→</span>
          <span class="node">86,000 customers</span>
        </div>
        <div class="flow">
          <span class="node">PEI Wind farms</span>
          <span class="arrow">→</span>
          <span class="node" style="opacity:.6">On-island grid<br><small>variable output</small></span>
        </div>
        <div class="note">On peak winter evenings, PEI demand can exceed cable capacity — requiring load management or controlled outages.</div>
      </div>

      <p>This structure creates a supply chain with a single critical chokepoint. A cable failure during a January cold snap — when demand peaks between 6–10 AM and 4–9 PM — would immediately push the island beyond what on-island generation can supply. On-island backup consists primarily of combustion turbines and whatever wind is producing at that moment.</p>
      <p>The January 2026 all-time demand record of <strong>403 MW</strong> exceeded the cable's 300 MW rated capacity, meaning load was managed through some combination of demand response, on-island generation, and real-time import management. The cable is physically rated higher than 300 MW in short bursts, but sustained operation above that level stresses the infrastructure.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="section">
    <h2 class="section-title">Wind: the local generator</h2>
    <div class="section-body">
      <p>PEI has a significant wind energy program, with turbines concentrated primarily along the island's north and south shores. Wind is the dominant source of on-island electricity generation — but it is inherently variable. When wind is strong and demand is moderate, PEI occasionally exports power to New Brunswick. When wind drops during peak demand, the cable makes up the difference.</p>
      <p>The dashboard tracks wind generation as a real-time percentage of island load. This number is the clearest single indicator of how much the island is relying on imports at any given moment. <strong>Wind at 80%+ of load</strong> means the island is near energy self-sufficient that hour. Wind at 10% during a cold evening means the cable is carrying close to its maximum.</p>
      <p>PEI has no utility-scale battery storage as of 2026. Each unit of wind that cannot be used immediately is either exported or curtailed. This limits the island's ability to buffer wind variability against demand peaks.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

