      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>

  <div class="section">
    <h2 class="section-title">Key risks</h2>
    <div class="risk-grid">
      <div class="risk-card high">
        <div class="risk-title">High — Cable failure in winter</div>
        <div class="risk-body">A submarine cable fault during peak demand (January–February, 4–9 PM) could leave PEI unable to meet load. On-island generation cannot sustain the full island without imports during cold weather.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="risk-card high">
        <div class="risk-title">High — NB Power supply disruption</div>
        <div class="risk-body">PEI has limited ability to negotiate around NB Power. A major generation shortfall in New Brunswick — from extreme cold, unplanned outages, or a large storm — directly constrains what is available for export to PEI.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="risk-card medium">
        <div class="risk-title">Medium — Demand growth outpacing cable</div>
        <div class="risk-body">The 403 MW January 2026 peak already exceeded the cable's rated capacity. EV adoption and heat pump deployment will increase winter peak demand further over the next decade without offsetting storage or generation additions.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="risk-card medium">
        <div class="risk-title">Medium — Storm damage to distribution</div>
        <div class="risk-body">Post-tropical storm Fiona (September 2022) caused widespread outages across PEI lasting days to weeks. The island's overhead distribution network remains exposed to major storm events.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="risk-card low">
        <div class="risk-title">Lower — Wind curtailment / export limits</div>
        <div class="risk-body">On high-wind, low-demand nights, PEI may need to curtail wind output. This is an economic issue more than a supply issue, but limits the return on wind investment without storage.</div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

